It's Working! 

It's working really well, just have to mount this new `acme-challenge` folder so that `certbot` and `nginx` container can write / read from the same source.

Here is my certbot command to renew my `api.mydomain.com`:

```
docker run --rm -it --name certbot \
  -v /home/myuser/letsencrypt:/etc/letsencrypt \
  -v /home/myuser/nginx/acme-challenge:/var/www/acme-challenge \
  certbot/certbot \
    certonly --webroot -w /var/www/acme-challenge/ -d api.mydomain.com --renew-by-default --email m@rokt.io --agree-tos --manual-public-ip-logging-ok --dry-run
```

I had to slightly modify my nginx configuration to make it work. Here is how I run my nginx container:

```
docker run --rm \
  -v /home/myuser/nginx/acme-challenge:/var/www/acme-challenge \
  -v /home/myuser/letsencrypt:/etc/nginx/letsencrypt \
  --name nginx-proxy \
  --link node-api \
  --link node-web \
  -p 80:80 \
  -p 443:443 \
  my-custom-nginx-container
```

I had to add this snippet to both vhost:

```
upstream api {
  server node-api:5000 max_fails=3;
}

...

# Force HTTPS
server {
  listen 80;
  ...
}

server {
  listen 443 ssl http2;
  server_name 		api.domain.com;
  ....

  include /etc/nginx/snippet/acme-challenge.conf;

  location / {
    ...
  }
}
```

And finally the acme-challenge snippet:

```
location ^~ /.well-known/acme-challenge/ {
  allow all;
  alias /var/www/acme-challenge/.well-known/acme-challenge/;
  default_type "text/plain";
}
```

And that's it! Thanks again to point me in the right direction ;)

